SIMPLE: folio
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Folio
<hw>Fol"io</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Folios</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Ablative of L.
<ets>folium</ets> leaf. See 4th <er>Foil</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
leaf of a book or manuscript.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sheet of paper once folded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A book made of sheets of paper each folded once
(four pages to the sheet); hence, a book of the largest kind. See Note
under <er>Paper</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The page number. The even folios
are on the left-hand pages and the odd folios on the
right-hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A page of a book; <fld>(Bookkeeping)</fld> a page in
an account book; sometimes, two opposite pages bearing the same serial
number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A leaf containing a certain number
of words, hence, a certain number of words in a writing, as in England,
in law proceedings 72, and in chancery, 90; in New York, 100
words.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Folio post</b></col>, <cd>a flat writing paper, usually
17 by 24 inches.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Folio</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Folio
<hw>Fol"io</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To put a serial number on each
folio or page of (a book); to page.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Folio</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Folio
<hw>Fol"io</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Formed of sheets each folded once,
making two leaves, or four pages; <as>as, a <ex>folio</ex> volume</as>.
See <er>Folio</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foliolate</ent>⟦br⟧
